Advance Directive Discussion note was completed on: Aug 5,2022
 
PRESENTING ISSUE: Advance Directive
 
Type of contact: Face-to-face
 
Writer met with:
  Veteran
  Family
    Details: XXXXX
 
Veteran was educated on their rights about Advance Directives and that VA 
does 
not discriminate against patients based on whether or not they have an 
advance 
directive.
 
Veteran was found to be alert and oriented x4 to person, place, time, and 
situation.
 
Writer discussed Advance Directives and Advance Care Planning with the 
Veteran.
Veteran was educated on the VA Advance Directive Forms, including the 
Living
Will, Durable Power of Attorney for Health Care and Treatment Preferences.
Veteran requested social work assistance with completing the forms today.
 
The following documents were provided: AD Form, What You Should Know 
About 
Advance Directives, Information for Patients: Common Life-Sustaining 
Treatments, Mental Health Care Preferences.
 
Veteran completed the VA Advance Directive Form, which is summarized 
below 
(please see actual form in VistA Imaging for full and complete legal 
information).
 
DURABLE POWER OF ATTORNEY FOR HEALTH CARE (DPAHC)
Veteran appoints the following person(s) as primary and alternate HCAs to 
make
health care decisions if there ever comes a time when Veteran is unable 
to 
make
those decisions.
  Appointed Primary HCA Name: Michael Oscar
                Relationship: Son
                     Address: 431 Gaither St Gaithersburge, MD 20877
                  Home Phone:
                  Work Phone:
                Mobile Phone: 469 231-0987
 
  Alternate Appointed HCA in the event the above named Primary HCA cannot 
or
  does not want to make health care decisions for the Veteran:
                        Name: Julia Oscar
                Relationship: daughter
                     Address: 431 Gaither St. Gaithersburge, MD 20877
                  Home Phone:
                  Work Phone:
                Mobile Phone: 468 3324432
 
LIVING WILL
This section allows Veteran to document how they want to be treated in 
case
they are unable to make decisions at any given time. The purpose is to
understand Veteran's treatment preferences and help to inform others when
making decisions on Veteran's behalf.
  Specific Preferences about Life-Sustaining Treatments:
    - If I am unconscious, in a coma, or in a vegetative state and
      there is little or no chance of recovery:
      No. I would not want life-sustaining treatments.
 
    - If I have permanent, severe brain damage that makes me unable to
      recognize my family or friends:
      I am not sure. It would depend on the circumstances.
 
    - If I have a permanent condition where other people must help me
      with my daily needs:
      Yes. I would want life-sustaining treatments.
 
    - If I need to use a breathing machine and be in bed for the
      rest of my life:
      No. I would not want life-sustaining treatments.
 
    - If I have pain or other severe symptoms that cause suffering
      and cannot be relieved:
      I am not sure. It would depend on the circumstances.
 
    - If I have a condition that will make me die very soon, even with
      life-sustaining treatments:
      No. I would not want life-sustaining treatments.
 
MENTAL HEALTH CARE PREFERENCES
Veteran does not wish to complete this section.
 
ADDITIONAL PREFERENCES (MEDICAL OR MENTAL HEALTH)
Veteran did not indicate additional preferences.
 
HOW STRICTLY VETERAN WANTS PREFERENCES FOLLOWED
Veteran wants preferences, as expressed in the Living Will, to be followed
STRICTLY, even if the person making decisions for me thinks that this is 
not 
in
my best interest.
 
DISPOSITION OF THE ADVANCE DIRECTIVE
The Veteran's VA Advance Directive was signed by the Veteran and two
appropriate witnesses per VHA Handbook 1004.02, dated December 24, 2013,
ADVANCE CARE PLANNING AND MANAGEMENT OF ADVANCE DIRECTIVES. The Veteran 
was
provided the original and additional copies for their HCA(s). Veteran is 
aware
they may contact this Writer or other trained team member at any time to 
make
changes or to revoke their Advance Directive. Appropriate contact 
information
was provided to Veteran. A copy of the Advance Directive was sent to the 
file
room for scanning into VistA Imaging.
